Yes, when the server sets `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to `*` (or any wildcard value), it indicates that any origin is allowed to make cross-origin requests to the server. This means that you can bypass the normal CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) restrictions and send requests from any domain without explicit permission.

However, this also means that the browser does not enforce CORS pre-flight checks, which are used to verify that the request method, headers, and credentials are allowed by the server. As a result, if your application sends an Authorization header in such a case, the browser will not automatically include it in the request, as it assumes that the server has already granted permission for all origins.

To include the Authorization header in such requests, you need to explicitly enable CORS pre-flight checks by adding the necessary CORS options to the server configuration. For example, in Node.js with Express, you can add the following middleware:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const cors = require('cors');
const app = express();

// Enable CORS pre-flight checks
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Methods', 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE');
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Authorization');
  res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Credentials', true);
  next();
});

// Add other middleware and routes here...

app.listen(3000);
```

This middleware adds the necessary CORS headers to the response of the pre-flight request, indicating which methods, headers, and credentials are allowed. By doing so, the browser will now automatically include the Authorization header in subsequent requests.

Note that setting `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` to `true` is required when sending cookies or other credentials, otherwise they will be ignored by the browser.

